flowRoot.flowPara: In this project, design of clockless circuits was explored. A clockless AES encryption module was designed, showing the feasability of implementing complex clockless circuits. Methods for production testing was also found.
Clockless circuits has previously been shown to have excellent properties such as low power consumption, low EMI, and robustness to circuit delays and difficult operating conditions.

Major obstacles for adopting clockless circuit design are the lack of well known design tools and workflows, and compatibility with industry standard design-for-test techniques. In this work, methods for designing clockless digital circuits will be explored by surveying the litterature and designing a clockless AES encryption circuit.

When designing clockless circuits, it is possible to express them in conventional languages, such as Verilog and VHDL. While there are done some work with this, most progress has been made with more specialized languages, emitting handshake circuits that can be translated to hardware.
Handshake circuits controls the flow of data in circuits by using local handshake signaling instead of a global clock, only consuming power at active areas in the circuit.

At Manchester University, a similar language, Balsa, was designed and released to the public domain, facilitating further research on the topic.

For this project, an AES encryption core was designed in the Balsa-language, and a new synthesis tool with support for automatic optimizations, Teak, was used to map the circuit into a working Verilog netlist. A survey was done to find methods for insertion of scan-chains for testing.
